<TEXT>
the peoples liberation army which crushed 
chinas prodemocracy movement is expected to play an increasingly 
important role in civilian politics 
it was lack of army support that doomed communist party general 
secretary zhao ziyang when he challenged senior leader deng 
xiaopings condemnation of student protesters for a freer society 
now that at least 150000 soldiers are stationed in and around 
beijing to enforce martial law cultivating the army will be a 
necessity for any replacement for zhao and prospective successor to 
the 84yearold deng 
which way the army will throw its support and whether it will 
stand united behind one candidate have become key questions but 
most foreign diplomats and military experts say they can do little 
more than guess 
one problem is that normal diplomatic and military contacts have 
been interrupted by the fighting in beijing outsiders have been 
reduced to watching which generals appear on television and reading 
between the lines in their speeches 
another is that the military stands outside the political 
dichotomy of liberals and conservatives defined by their stands on 
the speed of economic reform and degree of cultural freedom the 
military has its own priorities including stability and maintaining 
a political atmosphere in which the army has high status 
political initiatives are unlikely to come from the rank and 
file many of whom are illiterate and subjected to heavy propaganda 
young officers with relatively liberal educations might support 
reformers such as zhao but have little power 
the key players will be senior officers in their 50s and 60s who 
owe their positions to deng and are desirous of promotion and 
national stability 
by and large the conservatives seem to meet their interests best 
right now although longterm stability under a leadership that 
continues to repress the citizenry is dubious 
in the latest move army propaganda chief shao huaze took over as 
editor in chief of the partys official newspaper the peoples 
daily the paper said today that shao replaced tan wenrui who 
resigned for health reasons 
zhaos problems with the military began well before weeks of 
student protests for which he expressed sympathy threw the party 
leadership into crisis 
zhao was part of chinas rising young generation of leaders 
in their 50s and 60s who unlike deng and those in their 80s were 
not army officers in the pre1949 civil war and world war ii their 
rise was interpreted as part of a natural evolution from the heavily 
ideological politics of a revolutionary leadeship toward a more 
pragmatic and even technocratic government style 
but the status and budget of the military eroded steadily under 
the new leaders as funds were shifted from defense to economic 
development deng approved the shift but it appears zhao took the 
blame 
dengs personal power base was in the red army in which he 
served as political commissar during the 1930s and 1940s when it 
fought the nationalist government and japanese invaders he made 
zhao a vice chairman of the central military commission which he 
heads and which sets military policy 
the army reportedly remained lukewarm toward zhao who was more 
comfortable meeting diplomats and playing golf than visiting the 
troops when zhao cast his vote against a crackdown on the 
protesters and publicly blamed the growing chaos on deng not one 
army official rose to zhaos support according to foreign diplomats 
there clearly was opposition to orders to shoot the crowd 
protecting the students some units sat on the sidelines throughout 
the battling and never joined in there were reports never 
confirmed of individual soldiers or small groups firing on other 
soldiers who shot civilians 
but there were no reports of units opposing the political shakeup 
or contemplating an antideng coup 
clues in the official media indicate dengs candidate to succeed 
zhao is qiao shi a member of the partys top decisionmaking group 
he also lacks a military background but he may have an alternative 
acceptable to the senior officers he is believed in charge of 
chinas internal secret service and at one point was reported to 
oversee the peoples armed police which has links to the army 
there are no indications the army is preparing to throw up its 
own candidate the military has not put forward a political 
candidate since marshal lin piao fell from grace as mao tsetungs 
prospective heir in 1971 after allegedly plotting a coup 
one lesson may be drawn from the armys performance of the past 
few weeks even in the face of the hardest choice many soldiers 
probably have ever had to make to disobey orders or to shoot at 
people who had been giving them drinks and food for days as they sat 
parked in trucks around beijing discipline and unity prevailed 
when it comes time to rally behind a successor to deng the army 
likely will act as one 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
kathy wilhelm has reported from beijing for the 
associated press for two years 
</TEXT>
