<TEXT>
the battered tanker exxon valdez was pulled 
cautiously toward california today leaving behind stained 
shorelines and angry feelings from the nations worst oil spill 
i must say were not sorry to see it go gov steve cowper 
said at a news conference in juneau 
the 987foot vessel was stopped briefly for a scheduled look at 
its hull and video cameras were used to ensure that the punctured 
hull was sound before the damaged ship was towed into the often 
stormy gulf of alaska en route to a san diego drydock and more than 
25 million in repairs 
the 2500mile trip is expected to take about 20 days 
the exxon valdez rammed bligh reef on march 24 dumping almost 11 
million gallons of heavy north slope crude oil into the waters of 
prince william sound after the accident authorities pumped the 
remaining oil from the ship into other tankers 
the spill killed thousands of birds and sea mammals and spoiled 
hundreds of miles of coastline it also dealt a severe blow to 
alaskas 2 billion fishing industry forcing officials to ban 
postpone or restrict fishing 
the vessel unceremoniously lifted anchor friday and came under 
tow behind two 7000horsepower oceangoing tugboats 
a third tug was attached to the tankers stern a salvage boat 
trailed not far behind 
two escort vessels loaded with 9000 feet of containment boom and 
each carrying an oil skimming vessel with 4000 barrels capacity 
brought up the rear 
al kapp skipper of the journeyman out of california posted a 
handlettered sign on the side of his boat as he ushered the exxon 
valdez away thanks a lot exxon the sign said 
speaking by radio to a nearby media vessel kapp said fishing 
closures have hurt its disrupted my life its disrupted our 
industry 
progress initially was slow and the tanker moved only about two 
miles in the first two hours said exxon spokesman henry beathard 
the speed is expected to increase to about 5 mph 
coast guard spokeswoman brenda toledo said a light film of oil 
was reported on the water near the tanker as it got under way the 
source of the sheen was unclear she said adding not much oil is 
necessary to make a sheen were talking pints not gallons she 
said 
seven exxon officers and four salvage experts were aboard for the 
trip to san diego officials said 
the skeleton crew will monitor air pressure in the vessels cargo 
tanks conduct inspections and be ready to help with the ships 
engines should the vessel run into trouble 
exxon and the alyeska pipeline service co have been criticized 
for their slow handling of the spill during its first few days 
today oil with a sludgelike consistency can be found 700 miles 
from the reef 
the tankers former captain joseph hazelwood has pleaded 
innocent to three felony counts of criminal mischief and 
misdemeanors including negligent discharge of pollutants and 
operating a vessel while drunk he is free on 50000 bail 
