<TEXT>
dorcas r hardy says she is stepping down as 
head of social security satisfied the agency she modernized and 
streamlined sometimes in the face of sharp congressional criticism 
is in good shape 
but she warns that while overall public confidence in the program 
is justifiably high policies using social security trust funds to 
underwrite other government programs and reduce the federal budget 
deficit are fueling a lack of confidence in the program by 
younger workers 
social security continues to be misunderstood by 
beneficiaries taxpayers and elected officials alike and most 
younger workers do not trust that the government will preserve 
social security for their golden years she said in her letter 
of resignation to president bush on friday 
hardy said she has confidence in the future of the social 
security program but thats not to say everybody does 
and she said many workers are discouraged by a provision 
covering the working elderly that withholds 1 for every 2 they 
earn over 8880 a year a provision she has worked to repeal 
hardy 42 had sought to remain in the social security post she 
has held for three years but told the associated press the bush 
administration indicated to her she would be replaced 
the administration is expected to nominate gwendolyn king a 
former legislative aide to sen john heinz rpa who later headed 
the office of attorney general dick thornburgh when he was governor 
of pennsylvania according to sources who spoke on the condition of 
anonymity 
hardy said she will leave july 31 and plans to host a weekly 
syndicated television program about finances and explore other 
options in the private sector 
hardys tenure was marked by efforts to streamline and modernize 
the agency despite declines in staffing but critics on capitol hill 
said service at the agency has deteriorated 
among the criticisms against her was that new services she 
introduced have been implemented poorly and resulted in worse 
service to the public for example a tollfree telephone service to 
provide information to individuals on their benefits has come under 
fire for a high rate of busy signals and inaccurate information is 
given to callers 
a senate committee earlier this year asked whether social 
security was violating privacy rights through its practice since 
halted of verifying millions of social security numbers for private 
companies engaged in checking credit ratings 
and a house government operations subcommittee in march began an 
inquiry into whether hardy combined business trips with vacations 
and political campaigning for members of congress 
sen david pryor dark chairman of the special senate 
committee on aging and one of hardys harshest critics in congress 
said he hoped new leadership can recapture the original spirit of 
the agency to provide compassionate service to our most vulnerable 
citizens 
but hardy said the agency now has a plan that will lead a solvent 
trust fund into the next century and the vast majority of the 
public is very pleased with the service social security provides 
a trust fund that was considered shaky before she took office now 
has enough money to pay benefits until at least the middle of the 
next century according to a social security administration report 
in april 
