federal engineers say crash tests of 19 cars 
show drivers of the chevrolet astro van have the greatest chance of 
head injury in an accident 
the vans manufacturer general motors corp said the federal 
tests arent a valid indicator of crashworthiness 
the astro van was among 12 vehicles listed in the third round of 
crashtest results released friday by the national highway traffic 
safety administration the vehicles were tested under nhtsas 
program to provide consumers a guide to the safety of 1989 vehicles 
results of seven other vehicles had been released previously 
gm said the federal test results do not reflect the actual 
safety performance of these vehicles on the road because the test 
is done on only one vehicle 
the vehicles were smashed at 35 mph into a fixed barrier and the 
stresses that resulted were measured by sensors on humanshaped 
dummies protected by seat belts or other crashprotection devices 
nhtsa engineers reported stresses on the head as an index called 
the head injury criterion the higher the index the greater the 
likelihood of injury 
the astro van crash test produced a head injury criterion of 
1849 for the driverside dummy in the astro van nhtsa said the 
figure was more than double the head injury criterion recorded in a 
test of the mitsubishi van the only other van tested this year 
the mitsubishi had a head injury criterion of 805 nhtsa said 
federal regulations require cars on the market to produce a head 
injury criterion no greater than 1000 in tests conducted by the 
automakers the public tests done by nhtsa and the mandatory tests 
to meet safety regulations are not considered comparable because the 
automakers tests are done at 30 mph 
other new test results by weight class produced these driver head 
injury criteria 
subcompact cars mercury tracer 4door hatchback 940 
