<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration is taking 
action to stop airline manufacturers from placing exit doors too far 
apart 
the association of flight attendants praised fridays order 
which limits doors to within 60 feet apart saying it will stop 
boeing plans to remove middle doors over the wings of future jumbo 
jets 
but a boeing spokesman in seattle david jimenez said the 
aircraft builder already has abandoned any plans that would put exit 
doors in its planes further than 60 feet apart 
the faa said its order will hold the line on the growth of 
distances between airliner exit doors noting that one unidentified 
model was planned with exits more than 80 feet apart 
the new regulations published in fridays edition of the federal 
register take effect in 30 days and apply to all newly 
manufactured airplanes of older type designs after oct 16 1987 
when the rule was first proposed the faa said 
the rule also will prevent any modification of existing designs 
that would increase the distance between doors beyond 60 feet and 
prohibit us airlines from using foreign airplanes that have exit 
distances exceeding the new standard the agency said 
the faa said it is forming an advisory committee to set standards 
based on how quickly passengers can exit from the doors rather than 
on arbitrary distances between doors the committee is to make 
recommendations by july 1991 
the flight attendants group in a prepared statement said 
boeings plans would have created a 72foot distance between some of 
the planes exit doors 
the association had urged congress to save 747 exits over the 
wing saying passengers in many crashes have been unable to reach 
exits in postcrash fires 
jimenez said boeing had planned to remove two of the 10 exit 
doors on new 747s but abandoned the plan prior to the faa order he 
said the new order would not affect any boeing model 
previous faa rules have required require at least one exit door 
for every 55 seats 
the faa said all narrowbody airplanes and most widebody planes 
already conform to the new distance limit 
