a tiny rotating blade device was inserted 
surgically and used to slice away plaque to unclog a patients heart 
artery in a firstofitskind procedure a doctor at st luke 
medical center said 
cardiologist frank cummins said lawrence alfson 58 was the 
first patient in medical history to undergo an atherectomy in which 
an experimental blade device is used to clear plaque from a blocked 
heart artery 
cummins said he inserted the tiny blade device which was 
attached to a long tube into an artery in the patients leg and 
maneuvered it carefully to the heart 
the rotating blade sliced away the plaque which was then sucked 
out of the artery by a vacuum attached to the device the procedure 
successfully restored blood flow to alfsons heart cummins said 
the hope is that if you actually remove the plaque from the 
artery it wont narrow down again cummins said 
alfson said he had bypass surgery 10 years ago and a vein from 
his leg was grafted to the heart since then he has twice undergone 
angioplasty the use of a balloon to open the clogged blood vessel 
alfson said the experimental atherectomy took about two hours 
friday and was relatively painless he remained hospitalized 
saturday but the st lukes declined to release a condition report 
 
